#AD We have created a city guide that includes our favourite places to visit, eat, drink and shop in our home town of Aberdeen City, as part of @visitscotland #HameTownTourist campaign.

Swipe through the slider to see some of our highlights and then click the link in our bio to read the full guide over on @visitscotland iKnow community thread.

We would love to know who is also local to Aberdeen, and where your favourite spots are to visit in the city, let us know in the commenst below.

#HameTownTourist#ScotlandLovesLocal #VisitAbdn

Once the site of the infamous Nor' Loch, the fetid manmade swamp into which the sewage of medieval Edinburgh flowed, Princes Street Gardens, with its 37 acres of urban parkland, marks the boundary between the Old Town and New Town.

Huge thanks to @gisforgeorgina for this beautiful photograph of the Ross Fountain.

#hiddenscotland #visitscotland #Scotland #edinburgh

This beautiful pink castle is said to be the inspiration for Walt Disney's Cinderella Castle.

If you're planning a visit be sure to take a walk around one of the amazing woodland trails on offer, we recommend the Hill Trail (the red arrows).

Swipe left for more information.

for this beautiful photograph.

In the heart of the picturesque Cairngorms village of Carrbridge, be sure to pay a visit to the oldest stone bridge in the Highlands â The Old Packhorse Bridge, which dates back impressively to 1717.

Swipe left for more information.

One of the oldest castles in Scotland, this historic stronghold sits upon a volcanic plug in the Firth of Clyde and was at the heart of the ancient kingdom of Strathclyde.

Swipe left to learn more about Dumbarton Castle.

Huge thanks to @russell_davies for this amazing photograph.

#hiddenscotland #scotland #visitscotland

The Old Town by @snapsbyshirin is the name popularly given to the oldest part of Edinburgh and together with the New Town forms a UNESCO World Heritage Site. One end is closed by Edinburgh Castle and the Royal Mile leads away from it, with minor streets (called closes or wynds) budding off the main spine.
â«ï¸
The topography for the city is known as "crag and tail" and was created during the Ice Age. The hilltop crag was the earliest part of the city to develop, becoming fortified by Malcolm III and his wife, Saint Margaret of Scotland in the 11th century and eventually developing into the current Edinburgh Castle. The rest of the city grew slowly down the tail of land from the Castle Rock to the Palace of Holyrood.
â«ï¸
From the 1500s, the inhabitants, choosing to stay in proximity to the protection of the castle, built tall narrow buildings along a stretch known as Castlehill. By the time of the birth of Mary, Queen of Scots, in 1542, the Old Townâs characteristic pattern of narrow wynds and closes between high tenements was well established.
â«ï¸
Today, Old Town is one of the most popular areas to visit in Edinburgh and is home to many notable buildings including St Giles Cathedral, the Law Courts and the Royal Museum of Scotland, to name a few.
